data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` to verify the type, then cast. Your current code throws an `InvalidCastException` on failure instead of a clean test failure message.

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

Or with the generic overload (MSTest v2.2.8+):

```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
```

This gives a clear failure message like *"Expected type: EmailHandler, Actual type: SmsHandler"* instead of an unhandled exception.
